    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-18T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="206"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/10727a suppl.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-18T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 18, 1918, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2883. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 1643. <persName>Frothingham</persName>. Supplementing Department’s 2550, our
                    1538, October 31, 7 p.m., Embassy’s 3618, your 1846, November 11. In our view
                    licenses are allowed at discretion as exceptions to general rule of prohibition
                    because of the special circumstances of each particular case. Submission of
                    copies of permissions after allowance is not helpful because not practicable to
                    deduce therefrom any general rule to govern exceptional cases. Desirable that
                    there be harmony of action secured through conference as cases arise rather than
                    protest after action taken.</p>
                <p>Your suggestion respecting imports from northern neutrals corresponds to present
                    practice.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
